First, we need to understand the structure of a doubly stochastic matrix. 

A matrix $M \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ is doubly stochastic if each row and each column sums to 1. 

So for all $i \in \{1, \ldots, n\}$, $\sum_{j=1}^n M_{i,j} = 1$ and $\sum_{i=1}^n M_{i,j} = 1$.

Now, the permanent of $M$ is defined as:

$\text{Perm}(M) = \sum_{\sigma \in S_n} \prod_{i=1}^n M_{i, \sigma(i)}$

where $S_n$ is the set of all permutations of $\{1, 2, \ldots, n\}$.

